The Caio maior was writ- ten in the spring of 44 Μ. soon after Caesar’s death, and the De officiis was completed in November of the same year2. As Cicero was travelling during July and August, while September and October were occupied by the De officiis, and probably April and May by the De divinatione, we shall not greatly err if we suppose the Laelius to have been composed in June of the year 44 nc. It was a gloomy time for Cicero for many reasons, but particularly because the high hopes concerning politics which he entertained on Caesars death were already shattered.- The circumstances of the time are to a great extent reflected in the tone of the dialogue.
